I will change diapers on your desk.

282
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:21,900
Every birthday cake in the break room,
every retirement party,

283
00:17:21,900 --> 00:17:25,600
I will be there. Watching her.

284
00:17:25,600 --> 00:17:31,400
Well, I better get you a parking space.
Cause she's staying.

285
00:17:42,100 --> 00:17:45,100
Don't you think it spices up the room?

286
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:58,700
Oh, I was just letting you a gift.
To apologize for throwing gravel in your face.

287
00:17:59,400 --> 00:18:01,300
You didn't have to do that.

288
00:18:01,300 --> 00:18:04,700
I kind of did.
I want us to be friends.

289
00:18:04,700 --> 00:18:09,300
Yeah, well--
that's not going to happen.

290
00:18:09,300 --> 00:18:10,900
Why not?

291
00:18:10,900 --> 00:18:14,500
Aside from you blinding me,

292
00:18:14,500 --> 00:18:17,300
several weeks ago 
you freaked out in my house.

293
00:18:17,300 --> 00:18:21,500
You screamed,
you threw furniture around--

294
00:18:21,500 --> 00:18:26,900
OK. I realize I was at a run that night.
But I was upset.

295
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:30,100
You have to get over that.
For Julie's sake.

296
00:18:30,100 --> 00:18:31,100
For Julie's sake?

297
00:18:31,100 --> 00:18:32,300
How do you think it makes her feel

298
00:18:32,300 --> 00:18:35,000
that her mother and her boyfriend
can't even get along?

299
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:40,900
Zach, Julie does not think of you 
as her boyfriend.

300
00:18:40,900 --> 00:18:44,900
In fact, I don't think 
she wants anything to do with you.

301
00:18:44,900 --> 00:18:46,500
She said that?

302
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:47,400
Yeah.

303
00:18:47,400 --> 00:18:48,300
I don't believe you.

304
00:18:48,300 --> 00:18:50,900
Believe whatever you want.

305
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:53,800
If she did, it's because
you told her stuff about me that's not true!

306
00:18:53,800 --> 00:18:56,900
Zach! Come here!

307
00:18:56,900 --> 00:18:58,400
Right now!

308
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:07,900
Please. Don't ruin this for me.

309
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:32,100
How do you know Mary Alice?

310
00:19:32,100 --> 00:19:32,900
Who?

311
00:19:32,900 --> 00:19:37,700
Mary Alice Young.
She lives next door to me in Fairview.

312
00:19:37,700 --> 00:19:40,400
She's standing right here in this picture with you.

313
00:19:40,400 --> 00:19:44,500
That's Angela Forrest. We worked together
at the rehab center, 15 years ago.

314
00:19:44,500 --> 00:19:48,300
Don't be dense, Felicia.
Don't you think I know my own neighbor?

315
00:19:50,700 --> 00:19:53,400
Does this Mary Alice have children?

316
00:19:53,400 --> 00:19:57,300
A teenager. Her boy.

317
00:19:59,700 --> 00:20:01,700
What?

318
00:20:02,600 --> 00:20:06,700
Angela and I worked together 
with a very disturbed young woman

319
00:20:06,800 --> 00:20:09,200
who gave birth to a baby boy.

320
00:20:09,200 --> 00:20:13,300
About a year later,
Angela and her husband

321
00:20:13,300 --> 00:20:14,800
disappeared.

322
00:20:14,800 --> 00:20:19,700
Not long after that,
I heard that the child was missing too.

323
00:20:19,700 --> 00:20:22,400
People said it was just a coincidence.

324
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:28,400
But in my heart I always hoped
that she had given him a proper home.

325
00:20:28,400 --> 00:20:32,700
Are you saying
she stole the baby?

326
00:20:32,700 --> 00:20:38,200
Don't look shocked, Martha.
Makes your face look fat.

327
00:20:38,200 --> 00:20:42,300
The biological mother was a drug addict.

328
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:45,900
If Angela really is your neighbor,
which I doubt,

329
00:20:45,900 --> 00:20:50,500
then that child was very lucky.

330
00:21:10,800 --> 00:21:12,600
Lynette, hey!

331
00:21:12,600 --> 00:21:14,200
If you're looking for Tom,
he's out with a client.

332
00:21:14,200 --> 00:21:17,600
No. I actually wanted to see you.

333
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:20,100
That's really funny.
I was thinking the same thing.

334
00:21:20,100 --> 00:21:22,700
I've been here all this time.
We should go out.

335
00:21:22,700 --> 00:21:24,800
For lunch, just the two of us.

336
00:21:24,800 --> 00:21:27,600
Yeah, I'll check my book.

337
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:30,200
So Annabelle--

338
00:21:30,200 --> 00:21:33,300
do you have feelings for Tom?

339
00:21:33,300 --> 00:21:34,500
What?

340
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:35,900
You heard me.

341
00:21:35,900 --> 00:21:40,200
OK, you want to talk about this, Lynette?
Let's talk.

342
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:44,300
Yes, Tom and I were in love.
But he married you.

343
00:21:44,300 --> 00:21:48,600
I'm not looking to break up a happy couple.

344
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:52,200
Anyway, that's probably more your speed, isn't it?

345
00:21:52,200 --> 00:21:55,600
Morning, ladies.
Just gotten in for a little more fuel.

346
00:21:55,600 --> 00:22:00,100
Yeah, one man's sludge
is another man's liquid gold.

347
00:22:00,100 --> 00:22:03,300
Well, back to the trenches.

348
00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:08,100
Watch your step.
Tom and I are a team.

349
00:22:08,100 --> 00:22:12,300
Our marriage is rock solid.
Nothing you do could ever break that up.

350
00:22:12,300 --> 00:22:16,500
Then why are you down here right now,
warning me?

351
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:34,200
Gabrielle! What brings you down here?

352
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:38,200
Sweet mother of God,
what have you done this time?

353
00:22:38,200 --> 00:22:40,300
You're pregnant?
- Yes.

354
00:22:40,300 --> 00:22:42,800
And it's impossible, I'm on the pill!

355
00:22:42,800 --> 00:22:45,000
Which I know you probably think is a sin.
But it works.

356
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:47,700
It's a 99.9% effective sin.

357
00:22:47,700 --> 00:22:50,800
Maybe it's in that 1/10 of a percent
that God resides.

358
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:53,700
Couldn't wait to throw that in, could you?

359
00:22:53,700 --> 00:22:55,000
God is screwing with me.

360
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:58,400
He doesn't like how I live my life,
so he's punishing me.

361
00:22:58,400 --> 00:23:02,300
Have you done something
that would warrant being punished?

362
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:05,200
The gardener?

363
00:23:06,300 --> 00:23:07,600
I thought that was over.

364
00:23:07,600 --> 00:23:11,600
No, it was, and then--
He just happened to be there.

365
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:14,200
That's my point:
I'd be an awful mother.

366
00:23:14,200 --> 00:23:18,800
I'm selfish, I'm self-centered--
The only person more self-centered than me is Carlos.

367
00:23:18,800 --> 00:23:22,200
He's so self-centered that he doesn't even know
how self-centered I am.

368
00:23:22,200 --> 00:23:23,500
We'd be terrible parents.

369
00:23:23,500 --> 00:23:27,600
Gabrielle, I'd like to help.
But I'm not sure what it is you want.

370
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:30,900
I want to know who to be angry at.

371
00:23:30,900 --> 00:23:34,800
Here's a thought:
Don't be angry. Be thankful.

372
00:23:34,800 --> 00:23:37,100
Children are a gift, are they not?

373
00:23:39,600 --> 00:23:44,400
I don't have time for this crap.
I have a party to plan.

374
00:23:45,500 --> 00:23:49,300
Thanks.- Edie.
- Hi.

375
00:23:49,300 --> 00:23:50,600
Wow, things are really coming along.

376
00:23:50,600 --> 00:23:52,800
Yeah, slowly and expensively.

377
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:56,100
It'll be worth it.
You're doing an amazing job.

378
00:23:57,600 --> 00:24:02,900
So, look, you're basically a-- predator,
and I need some advice.

379
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:09,300
... and I know Tom loves me,
but I don't trust this woman.

380
00:24:09,300 --> 00:24:11,600
I think there's an agenda there.

381
00:24:11,600 --> 00:24:14,100
I don't know. I bet I'm being paranoid.

382
00:24:14,100 --> 00:24:17,300
No, you did the right thing coming to me.

383
00:24:17,300 --> 00:24:20,100
There are two ways to approach this.

384
00:24:20,100 --> 00:24:23,000
But first I have to ask:
What kind of shape is this woman in?

385
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:25,400
Fantastic shape. She's gorgeous.

386
00:24:25,400 --> 00:24:28,900
OK. Now there's only one way to approach this.

387
00:24:28,900 --> 00:24:30,700
You're gonna have to act fast.

388
00:24:30,700 --> 00:24:31,500
I'm listening.

389
00:24:31,500 --> 00:24:35,100
It's really pretty simple.
When I feel threatened by a woman,

390
00:24:35,100 --> 00:24:38,300
I pull her in.
I make her my best friend.

391
00:24:38,300 --> 00:24:40,800
I thought you said
you didn't have any female friends.

392
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:42,300
I don't.

393
00:24:42,300 --> 00:24:45,300
And I've never felt threatened by a woman either.

394
00:24:45,300 --> 00:24:47,500
But the point is:

395
00:24:47,500 --> 00:24:48,900
Keep your friends close,...

396
00:24:48,900 --> 00:24:52,900
... keep your enemies closer.

397
00:24:57,600 --> 00:25:03,000
Tom, we're having a dinner party.
I'm thinking of inviting Annabelle.

398
00:25:05,800 --> 00:25:08,600
We're not moving.
- Susan knows something.

399
00:25:08,600 --> 00:25:10,700
Edie said she--
- I don't care what Edie Britt said!

400
00:25:10,700 --> 00:25:11,900
I'm not leaving Julie!

401
00:25:11,900 --> 00:25:16,100
You want to risk our lives, our future
over some schoolyard crush?

402
00:25:16,100 --> 00:25:19,200
It's more than that.
Julie loves me.

403
00:25:19,200 --> 00:25:21,800
Then why does she refuse to see you?

404
00:25:21,800 --> 00:25:25,300
Mrs Mayer lies to her.
If it wasn't for that, she would be with me.

405
00:25:25,300 --> 00:25:27,000
Are you sure?

406
00:25:27,800 --> 00:25:30,300
You know, Julie is a-- very special girl.

407
00:25:30,300 --> 00:25:30,600
I know.

408
00:25:30,600 --> 00:25:34,600
She could have just about any boy she wanted.

409
00:25:35,300 --> 00:25:39,500
I think you're a wonderful kid.
I do, but--

410
00:25:39,500 --> 00:25:43,600
you're not that special, Zach.

411
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:46,200
Not really.

412
00:25:46,300 --> 00:25:47,700
She kissed me.

413
00:25:48,300 --> 00:25:49,800
Lately?

414
00:25:52,100 --> 00:25:54,000
Let's pack our bags and get out of here.

415
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:56,600
We can leave this whole mess behind,
start over.

416
00:25:56,600 --> 00:25:59,500
And there will be other girls,
I promise.

417
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:01,200
No!

418
00:26:01,200 --> 00:26:03,300
If Susan goes to the police, it's over.

419
00:26:03,300 --> 00:26:06,300
They'll take me away.
They'll take you away. Don't you get that?

420
00:26:06,300 --> 00:26:09,400
If Julie doesn't love me anymore,
then it doesn't matter.

421
00:26:09,400 --> 00:26:11,600
None of it matters.

422
00:26:19,400 --> 00:26:22,300
Magruder had absolutely no idea 
what was going on.

423
00:26:22,300 --> 00:26:26,700
During the entire campaign,
he was practically holding Benson's hand!

424
00:26:26,700 --> 00:26:30,900
After the way they burned them, screwed them over! 
That was too...

425
00:26:30,900 --> 00:26:35,800
It was awful!

426
00:26:35,800 --> 00:26:38,700
Excuse me, I need to get in here
so I can clear the plates.

427
00:26:38,700 --> 00:26:42,100
You want some help with that?

428
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:43,500
Looks like we got company.

429
00:26:43,500 --> 00:26:45,400
Hey guys, isn't it time for bed?

430
00:26:45,400 --> 00:26:48,800
Oh, they never get to see you.
Let them stay up for a while.

431
00:26:48,800 --> 00:26:52,300
OK, come here!
I want you to meet someone.

432
00:26:53,400 --> 00:26:55,800
This is Miss Foster.

433
00:26:55,800 --> 00:26:56,600
Hi.

434
00:26:56,600 --> 00:27:01,600
She's an old, old friend of your daddy's.

435
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:04,500
Hey, what you got there?
- It's a picture we painted.

436
00:27:04,500 --> 00:27:06,900
Let me have a look at that.

437
00:27:06,900 --> 00:27:10,500
It's all of us with Mommy and Daddy.
We're really happy.

438
00:27:10,500 --> 00:27:13,800
It's so adorable.
When did you do this?

439
00:27:13,800 --> 00:27:16,700
Today, Mom told us to.

440
00:27:16,700 --> 00:27:19,600
I just told them to paint something nice.
The sentiment's all theirs.

441
00:27:19,600 --> 00:27:23,300
But you told us to--
- Hold on, honey, grown-ups are talking.

442
00:27:23,300 --> 00:27:26,100
Well, this is really neat.

443
00:27:26,100 --> 00:27:29,600
How would you boys like to
paint my portrait one day?

444
00:27:29,600 --> 00:27:32,400
Sure, you're pretty.
- OK, great.

445
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:34,700
Like your dad said, it's time for bed.

446
00:27:34,700 --> 00:27:37,100
I'll take them back upstairs.

447
00:27:37,100 --> 00:27:39,000
Come on, guys!

448
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:41,100
Thank you.

449
00:27:46,900 --> 00:27:48,200
I must say, Lynette.

450
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:52,400
Your home is warm and inviting,
your children are absolutely precious--

451
00:27:52,400 --> 00:27:56,400
this whole evening was practically
a commercial for the perfect family.

452
00:27:56,400 --> 00:27:59,000
You think?

453
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:04,200
You couldn't have planned it any better.
And I mean that.

454
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:07,200
Good.

455
00:28:11,900 --> 00:28:14,300
Hello, Susan.

456
00:28:14,300 --> 00:28:17,300
Oh. Hi.

457
00:28:17,300 --> 00:28:21,700
I understand you and Edie went
snooping through my house.

458
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:22,600
Huh?

459
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:25,100
It's OK. I'm not mad.

460
00:28:25,100 --> 00:28:28,800
So, what do you want to know about Angela?

461
00:28:31,200 --> 00:28:35,700
It was Mary Alice's birth name.
She was named after her aunt Angela.

462
00:28:35,700 --> 00:28:39,800
When she was a teenager there were falling-outs.
So she changed her name into Mary Alice.

463
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:45,000
This is before we were married,
so you'll forgive me if I'm hazy on the details.

464
00:28:45,300 --> 00:28:48,400
That's it?
That's the explanation?

465
00:28:48,400 --> 00:28:52,000
Ridiculously simple, isn't it?

466
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:57,000
She changed her name because
she got in a fight with her aunt?

467
00:28:57,000 --> 00:28:59,500
That doesn't seem like something
Mary Alice would do.

468
00:28:59,500 --> 00:29:05,100
Neither did suicide,
but we both know that she did it.

469
00:29:05,100 --> 00:29:09,000
So can we finally put this behind us?

470
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:11,200
Or do you need to break into my home
for anything else?

471
00:29:12,700 --> 00:29:14,300
Uh--

472
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:21,300
No.
I'm good. Thanks.

473
00:29:23,600 --> 00:29:24,700
Although--

474
00:29:24,700 --> 00:29:28,500
if you wouldn't mind,
I'd rather like to see that videotape I found.

475
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:30,100
The one marked "Angela."

476
00:29:31,400 --> 00:29:34,000
Would be nice to see Mary Alice
when she was young.

477
00:29:34,900 --> 00:29:38,800
I'm afraid that box of tapes
was thrown out with the trash.

478
00:29:41,300 --> 00:29:42,900
OK then.

479
00:29:43,200 --> 00:29:45,400
Susan--

480
00:29:45,400 --> 00:29:48,800
I'm serious when I say
I hope you'll leave my family alone now.

481
00:29:48,800 --> 00:29:53,600
This endless suspicion of yours
has become very tiring.

482
00:29:53,600 --> 00:29:56,400
I couldn't agree more.

483
00:30:09,400 --> 00:30:13,300
Oh. That's my cell, sorry.

484
00:30:17,100 --> 00:30:21,500
Oh God, it's Peterson. Excuse me.
- Peterson?

485
00:30:21,500 --> 00:30:23,400
Hello? Yeah.

486
00:30:26,700 --> 00:30:29,400
That was quite a show you put on tonight.

487
00:30:30,300 --> 00:30:31,400
Show?

488
00:30:32,700 --> 00:30:36,300
The boys' paintings,
all those references to how happy we are--

489
00:30:36,300 --> 00:30:38,700
What's wrong with subtly reminding Annabelle
that you're happily married?

490
00:30:38,700 --> 00:30:41,400
Because it wasn't subtle.

491
00:30:41,600 --> 00:30:43,800
And it's an insult to me.

492
00:30:45,100 --> 00:30:48,000
I did not mean it that way.

493
00:30:50,400 --> 00:30:53,400
Are you so insecure that you
have to pull that crap?

494
00:30:53,400 --> 00:30:56,400
Keep your voice down!

495
00:30:56,600 --> 00:31:00,600
It doesn't matter if she has feelings for me
as long as I'm not interested.

496
00:31:00,600 --> 00:31:03,500
Have I ever, ever
given you any reason to doubt me?

497
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:08,200
Anyone is capable of anything.
The first time we ever met, you were cheating.

498
00:31:08,200 --> 00:31:10,300
With you! Cheating with you!

499
00:31:10,300 --> 00:31:11,700
It's a pattern of behavior.

500
00:31:11,700 --> 00:31:13,600
Uh, give me a break!

501
00:31:13,600 --> 00:31:15,300
What am I supposed to do?

502
00:31:15,300 --> 00:31:19,200
You hire your old girlfriend and
you don't tell me about it for 3 months?

503
00:31:19,200 --> 00:31:22,300
I could've told you from Day One
and you'd still be jumping at my throat.

504
00:31:22,300 --> 00:31:24,700
Annabelle is ancient history.

505
00:31:24,700 --> 00:31:26,000
She's in the next room.

506
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:30,300
How long do we have to be married, Lynette,
until you actually trust me?

507
00:31:30,300 --> 00:31:31,500
I trust you.

508
00:31:31,500 --> 00:31:33,400
How many times have you said to me:
"If you ever touch another woman,

509
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:37,300
"I'll take the boys and walk out of here
and you'll never see us again!"

510
00:31:37,300 --> 00:31:40,400
That's just something
wives say to their husbands.

511
00:31:40,400 --> 00:31:43,500
Not all wives.

512
00:31:43,500 --> 00:31:47,000
You're so convinced that I'll be unfaithful!

513
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:50,900
It makes me sick!
The distrust, the paranoia,--

514
00:31:50,900 --> 00:31:57,900
It seems like you won't be happy until you
drive me out of this marriage to prove yourself right!

515
00:31:57,900 --> 00:32:01,400
Wait. Forget I said that.

516
00:32:01,400 --> 00:32:05,000
It's too late.
You said it.

517
00:32:05,300 --> 00:32:10,100
Well, then just consider it something
husbands say to their wives.

518
00:32:11,400 --> 00:32:17,000
Peterson's on cloud nine.
He discovered some inside scoop on the Metro account.

519
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:20,500
The bad news is,
we'll have to redo the entire presentation.

520
00:32:20,500 --> 00:32:21,500
Tonight?

521
00:32:21,500 --> 00:32:22,800
He'll need it first thing in the morning.

522
00:32:22,800 --> 00:32:26,300
Peterson says we might be pulling an all-nighter.

523
00:32:26,300 --> 00:32:28,300
I can't drive. I've been drinking.

524
00:32:28,300 --> 00:32:31,400
I'll drive. Come on.
- Thanks.

525
00:32:31,400 --> 00:32:35,400
Don't worry, Lynette.
I'll deliver him back to you as soon as I can.

526
00:32:36,600 --> 00:32:38,500
Please do.

527
00:32:52,400 --> 00:32:56,000
Honey, take over for a minute.
I'm giving a speech.

528
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:58,300
Make sure they stay pink like that, OK?

529
00:32:59,200 --> 00:33:01,000
Are you OK?

530
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:09,300
Oh. I just--
realize how disgusting meat can be.

531
00:33:09,300 --> 00:33:13,400
Everyone, I just want to say
it means a lot to me that you all came,

532
00:33:13,400 --> 00:33:18,400
and as you know, in a few days
I'll be taking a little government-sponsored vacation.

533
00:33:18,400 --> 00:33:22,100
Lucky for me, breakfast is included.

534
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:24,800
Oh God.

535
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:28,500
The bottom line is,
I'm going away to jail.

536
00:33:28,500 --> 00:33:33,700
And when a man has to go to jail,
which I hope none of you will ever have to do,

537
00:33:33,700 --> 00:33:36,100
he sees who his real friends are.

538
00:33:36,100 --> 00:33:38,600
So thanks.

539
00:33:38,900 --> 00:33:40,500
Cheers!

540
00:33:48,300 --> 00:33:50,700
Excuse you.

541
00:33:53,400 --> 00:33:57,600
Stay put until I need you.
Don't talk to anybody and, for God's sake,

542
00:33:57,600 --> 00:33:58,800
don't get drunk!

543
00:33:58,800 --> 00:34:00,700
You know I was supposed to
go to my cousin's wedding today.

544
00:34:00,700 --> 00:34:04,900
It's not a wedding, it's a commitment.
So sit down and

545
00:34:04,900 --> 00:34:07,600
try to fit in.

546
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:15,900
Urghh.

547
00:34:27,200 --> 00:34:29,000
Got you a hot dog.

548
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:30,500
No thanks. I'm full.

549
00:34:30,500 --> 00:34:34,300
They have a croquet set.
You wanna go hit some balls?

550
00:34:34,300 --> 00:34:35,400
No.

551
00:34:35,400 --> 00:34:37,100
That's fine. We can just sit here.

552
00:34:37,100 --> 00:34:38,100
Zach!

553
00:34:39,300 --> 00:34:40,000
I don't want to be your girlfriend.

554
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:46,400
I don't want to hang out with you.
I just want you to leave me alone, OK?

555
00:34:46,400 --> 00:34:48,000
OK--

556
00:35:28,300 --> 00:35:30,800
In that moment,

557
00:35:30,800 --> 00:35:34,000
while looking at the pills
that had been so obviously tampered with,

558
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:40,100
Gabrielle's nausea was suddenly replaced
by an even stronger sensation:

559
00:35:40,100 --> 00:35:41,700
rage.

560
00:35:58,700 --> 00:36:00,100
What are you doing?

561
00:36:00,600 --> 00:36:03,200
I'm so sorry.
That was an accident.

562
00:36:03,200 --> 00:36:05,700
Answer my question:
What are you doing here?

563
00:36:05,700 --> 00:36:07,000
I was invited.

564
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,800
By who?
- You know what, Dr Van de Kamp?

565
00:36:09,800 --> 00:36:12,400
I don't believe I have to answer to you.
- I think you do.

566
00:36:12,400 --> 00:36:13,500
What's going on here?

567
00:36:13,500 --> 00:36:17,400
He crashed the party.
This guy clearly is not taking "no" for an answer.

568
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:20,700
It's OK. George has a girlfriend.

569
00:36:20,700 --> 00:36:21,800
You brought her, didn't you?

570
00:36:21,800 --> 00:36:24,500
He doesn't have a girlfriend.
- I do, sir.

571
00:36:24,500 --> 00:36:26,300
She's right over there.

572
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:31,300
That's his girlfriend?

573
00:36:31,300 --> 00:36:34,900
See? You were worried for nothing.

574
00:36:34,900 --> 00:36:39,500
So, any time you want to apologize--

575
00:36:39,600 --> 00:36:44,300
Come on, Rex.
You owe George some sort of gesture.

576
00:36:49,700 --> 00:36:52,400
What the hell.

577
00:37:00,900 --> 00:37:03,000
Rex! Have you lost your mind?

578
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:06,000
To be fair, I only pushed him.

579
00:37:07,200 --> 00:37:09,000
Carlos! You son of a bitch!

580
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:12,200
I am pregnant and it's all your fault!

581
00:37:19,800 --> 00:37:20,700
Wow.

582
00:37:20,700 --> 00:37:24,100
This is turning into one hell of a party.

583
00:37:28,900 --> 00:37:31,000
Are you OK?

584
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:34,800
I think I can honestly say:
No. I'm not.

585
00:37:34,800 --> 00:37:37,400
I'm so sorry.

586
00:37:37,400 --> 00:37:39,100
Thanks.

587
00:37:39,100 --> 00:37:42,400
But you know what they say about kids:

588
00:37:42,400 --> 00:37:45,100
that you can't imagine having them
until you do,

589
00:37:45,100 --> 00:37:48,700
and then you can't imagine
life without them?

590
00:37:48,700 --> 00:37:50,300
It's true.

591
00:37:53,800 --> 00:37:58,500
All I'm saying is,
maybe this is a blessing in disguise.

592
00:37:58,500 --> 00:38:01,200
I don't know who the father is.

593
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:04,200
What?
- Yeah.

594
00:38:04,200 --> 00:38:07,100
So you mean you and John have still been...
- Yeah.

595
00:38:07,100 --> 00:38:08,300
Gabby!

596
00:38:08,300 --> 00:38:10,700
I know, Susan! I don't know what to do!

597
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:14,100
Oh! Oh my God!

598
00:38:14,100 --> 00:38:15,400
That-- that's my house!

599
00:38:15,400 --> 00:38:21,300
Call 911?
- Yes, that's my house!

600
00:38:22,600 --> 00:38:27,600
Oh, look, my kitchen!
Oh, it's a big fire!

601
00:38:29,700 --> 00:38:33,700
Turns out someone left the gas on
with candles burning.

602
00:38:33,700 --> 00:38:38,100
That's impossible.
We don't burn candles during the day.

603
00:38:38,100 --> 00:38:43,700
Uh, well-- I-- did have
a French vanilla candle burning earlier, but--

604
00:38:43,700 --> 00:38:46,000
I'm almost positive I blew it out!

605
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:47,900
You're almost positive?

606
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:54,100
Yes! I did! I-- I think.

607
00:38:54,100 --> 00:38:58,900
You're lucky the fire was contained.
The damage could've been far more extensive.

608
00:38:58,900 --> 00:39:02,500
You've got to be more careful from now on.

609
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:12,600
Don't worry. We will be.

610
00:39:17,700 --> 00:39:20,300
Bree, hi.
- Hi.

611
00:39:20,900 --> 00:39:21,900
You left the party so quickly,

612
00:39:21,900 --> 00:39:26,900
I didn't have a chance to apologize to you
for what Rex did.

613
00:39:26,900 --> 00:39:31,300
Oh George, I'm so sorry
he humiliated you in front of all these people.

614
00:39:31,300 --> 00:39:33,000
I don't know what got into him.

615
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:35,500
Isn't it obvious?
He hates me.

616
00:39:35,500 --> 00:39:40,500
No, he doesn't hate you.
He really doesn't even know you, and you don't know him.

617
00:39:40,500 --> 00:39:44,200
I know this much:
he won't let us be friends.

618
00:39:45,400 --> 00:39:48,700
Well, that's not his choice to make.

619
00:39:48,700 --> 00:39:52,500
What if he asked you not to see me anymore?

620
00:39:52,500 --> 00:39:54,900
What if he orders you not to?

621
00:39:54,900 --> 00:39:56,300
Well--

622
00:39:56,300 --> 00:40:00,100
I decide who I need in my life,
and I've decided that I need you.

623
00:40:00,100 --> 00:40:03,300
That's all there is to it.

624
00:40:03,300 --> 00:40:06,800
He could make it awfully difficult
for you to spend time with me.

625
00:40:06,800 --> 00:40:08,100
Well--

626
00:40:08,100 --> 00:40:12,100
Who says he has to know
how I spend my free time?

627
00:40:24,600 --> 00:40:28,000
I'm having trouble 
with a family across the street.

628
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:31,300
I think one of them 
may have set a fire in my house,

629
00:40:31,300 --> 00:40:33,000
and I don't know why, but

630
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:40,500
I feel like it's got something to do with
my friend who killed herself.

631
00:40:40,500 --> 00:40:44,600
I called the police,
but they didn't take me seriously.

632
00:40:45,500 --> 00:40:49,700
This family has got a secret.
A bad secret.

633
00:40:49,700 --> 00:40:51,000
I think I'm in over my head.

634
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:57,500
I need you to find out everything about
Paul Young and his family.

635
00:40:58,100 --> 00:41:00,500
Do you think you can help me?

636
00:41:01,600 --> 00:41:07,300
As a matter of fact,
I know I can.

637
00:41:11,400 --> 00:41:15,700
Spring comes every year to Wisteria Lane.

638
00:41:15,700 --> 00:41:21,300
But not everyone remembers to
stop and smell the flowers.

639
00:41:21,300 --> 00:41:27,300
Some are too busy
worrying about the future

640
00:41:27,300 --> 00:41:33,100
or mistakes they've made in the past.

641
00:41:33,100 --> 00:41:37,000
Others are preoccupied with not getting caught,

642
00:41:39,900 --> 00:41:41,500
It's a window!

643
00:41:41,500 --> 00:41:51,600
or thinking of ways
to catch someone else.

644
00:41:51,600 --> 00:41:57,100
Still, there will always be a few
who remember to take a moment

645
00:41:57,100 --> 00:42:00,600
and appreciate what Spring has given them,

646
00:42:03,300 --> 00:42:09,200
just as there will always be those who
prefer to sit in the dark,

647
00:42:09,200 --> 00:42:15,700
brooding over everything they've lost.

